<Layout title="Hoare/Effects.lean — Boolean effect embedding" favicon="✏️">
  <main>
    <a href="/reading/lean/" class="text-sm mb-4 inline-block">&larr; back to lean navigator</a>

    <h1>Hoare/Effects.lean</h1>
    <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mb-6"><a href="https://github.com/kimjune01/natural-framework/blob/master/NaturalFramework/Hoare/Effects.lean">View source on GitHub</a></p>

    <div class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-5 mb-8 callout">
      <p class="text-lg" style="max-width:none">Embeds Boolean contracts as &#123;0,1&#125;-valued effects &mdash; the simplest case of effectus theory (Cho and Jacobs, 2015), bridging contracts to the effect algebra world. Another entry in the <a href="https://june.kim/framework-lexicon">cross-community translation table</a>.</p>
    </div>

    <h3>structure Effect</h3>
    <p>An effect on type b: a function assigning a natural number value to each element, bounded above. When the bound is 1, this is a Boolean predicate (true/false). This approximates the [0,1]-valued effects of Cho-Jacobs using natural numbers.</p>
    <pre class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-4 font-mono text-sm text-blue-300"><code><span class="text-blue-300">structure</span> <span class="text-green-300">Effect</span> (&beta; : Type) <span class="text-blue-300">where</span>
  eval : &beta; &rarr; Nat
  bound : Nat
  bounded : &forall; b : &beta;, eval b &le; bound</code></pre>

    <h3>def booleanEffect</h3>
    <p>Embed a decidable Boolean contract (<code>b &rarr; Bool</code>) as a &#123;0,1&#125;-valued effect. True maps to 1, false maps to 0, bound is 1.</p>

    <h3>def effectPreserving</h3>
    <p>A kernel preserves an effect if every reachable output has effect value equal to the bound (fully satisfied). For Boolean effects this means <code>eval b = 1</code> for all outputs &mdash; exactly ContractPreserving.</p>

    <h3>theorem boolean_effect_bridge</h3>
    <p>The key equivalence: for Boolean effects, <code>effectPreserving</code> is exactly <code>ContractPreserving</code>. Boolean contracts are the &#123;0,1&#125; case of effect algebra predicates.</p>
    <pre class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-4 font-mono text-sm text-blue-300"><code><span class="text-blue-300">theorem</span> <span class="text-green-300">boolean_effect_bridge</span> [Monad M] [Support M]
    &#123;f : Kernel M &alpha; &beta;&#125; &#123;Q : &beta; &rarr; Bool&#125;
    : effectPreserving f (booleanEffect Q) &harr;
      ContractPreserving f (<span class="text-blue-300">fun</span> b =&gt; Q b = true)</code></pre>

    <h3>Effect.top / Effect.bot / Effect.and</h3>
    <p>Basic effect algebra operations: top (always 1), bottom (always 0), conjunction (min of two effects). These are the building blocks, though the full Cho-Jacobs effect algebra (partial addition, orthocomplement) is not formalized here.</p>

    <h3>theorem effectPreserving_comp</h3>
    <p>Closure under precomposition: if g preserves an effect, then <code>f;g</code> preserves it for any f. Only the last kernel's effect matters.</p>

